{{Infobox organization |name = Canadian Indigenous Nurses Association |image =Canadian Indigenous Nurses Association logo.png |image_border = |size = 175px |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = CINA |motto = |formation = |extinction = |type = Scientific, education |status = active |purpose = professional [[nursing]] organization for [[Indigenous peoples in Canada]]. |headquarters = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] |location = |region_served = Canada |membership = |language = [[English Language|English]], [[French language|French]] |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = [[Canadian Nurses Association]]. |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = {{url|www.indigenousnurses.ca}} |remarks = }}
The '''Canadian Indigenous Nurses Association''' (CINA) is a non-governmental, non-profit organization. It is an affiliate group of the [[Canadian Nurses Association]]. The CINA is the only professional [[nursing]] organization for [[Indigenous peoples in Canada]] and was formerly known as the Aboriginal Nurses Association of Canada. [[Ann Thomas Callahan]], a Cree Canadian nurse, was involved in its creation,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mary Jane Logan McCallum|author2=Adele Perry|title=Structures of Indifference: An Indigenous Life and Death in a Canadian City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MVJtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT58 |year=2018|publisher=University of Manitoba Press|isbn=978-0-88755-571-8|page=58}}</ref> and the association presented her with a Lifetime Achievement Award in 2014.<ref name=degrees>[https://www.degreesmagazine.ca/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/dm-ss2015.pdf ''Degrees''], Spring/Summer 2015, p. 9</ref>
