{{Infobox company | name = GTx, Inc. | logo = | type = [[Public company|Public]] | traded_as = {{NASDAQ|GTXI}} | foundation = September 24, 1997 | location = [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]], [[United States]] | key_people = | industry = [[Pharmaceutical company|Pharmaceuticals]] | products = [[Enobosarm]] | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | num_employees = | homepage = [http://www.gtxinc.com/ GTxInc.com] }}
'''GTx, Inc''' is a [[pharmaceutical company]] that is working on drugs in the [[selective estrogen receptor modulator]] (SERM) and [[selective androgen receptor modulator]] (SARM) classes. Its drugs in development include [[enobosarm]] (ostarine) and [[GTx-758]].
The company was founded in Memphis in 1997 by Mitch Steiner and Marc S. Hanover.<ref name=S1A/> The company was originally called Genotherapeutics, changed its name to GTx, Inc. in 2001, and reincorporated in Delaware in 2003.<ref name=S1A>{{cite web|title=GTX, INC. - FORM S-1/A|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1260990/000089161803006388/g85196a2sv1za.htm|publisher=Gtx via SEC Edgar|date=22 December 2003}}</ref> The company licensed [[toremifene]] from Orion Corporation, and licensed andarine, enobosarm and prostarine from the University of Tennessee Research Foundation; the SARM compounds from Tennessee had been invented by Karen Veverka and Michael Whitt and each later joined the company.<ref name=S1A/> The company held its IPO in February 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pritchard|first1=Carolyn|title=GTX prices IPO of 5.4 mln shares at $14.50 each|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/gtx-prices-ipo-of-54-mln-shares-at-1450-each|work=MarketWatch|date=2 February 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hennessey|first1=Raymond|title=With a Busy IPO Week Ahead,Mixed Reviews for 3 Offerings|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB107582803942119330|work=Wall Street Journal|date=4 February 2004}}</ref>
In 2006 GTx signed a partnership with [[Ipsen]] to develop toremifene, a selective estrogen receptor modulatorm to prevent prostate cancer and to prevent bone loss in men with prostate cancer; the FDA rejected the application to market the drug for this use in 2009, and Ipsen terminated the arrangement in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=John|title=GTx shares blitzed by FDA's toremifene rejection|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/gtx-shares-blitzed-by-fda-s-toremifene-rejection|work=FierceBiotech|date=2 November 2009|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=John|title=Ipsen bows out of troubled toremifene pact with GTx|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/ipsen-bows-out-of-troubled-toremifene-pact-gtx|work=FierceBiotech|date=2 March 2011|language=en}}</ref> In 2012 GTx sold its rights to toremifene to ProStrakan, a subsidiary of [[Kyowa Hakko Kirin]], for around $19 million, and terminated its agreement with Orion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Press release: GTx Announces Sale of Fareston|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/gtx-announces-sale-of-fareston%C2%AE|work=GTx via FierceBiotech|date=2 October 2012}}</ref>
By 2007 enobosarm was in a Phase II trial, and that year Gtx signed an exclusive license agreement for its SARM program with Merck; Merck bought $30M in GtX stock, paid an upfront fee of $40M, and agreed to fund $15M in research over the next three years. The agreement also included royalties on any product brought to market and around $400M in [[biodollars]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nagle|first1=Mike|title=Merck flexes muscle with GTx deal|url=https://www.outsourcing-pharma.com/Article/2007/11/07/Merck-flexes-muscle-with-GTx-deal|work=Outsourcing Pharma|date=7 November 2007}}</ref> The companies ended the deal in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swanekamp|first1=Kelsey|title=Merck And GTx Go Their Separate Ways|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/03/15/gtx-merck-pharma-markets-equities-drug-trial.html#14c838625e4b|work=Forbes|date=15 March 2010|language=en}}</ref>
In August 2013 GTx announced that enobosarm had failed in two Phase III clinical trials to treat wasting in people with lung cancer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enobosarm fails endpoints in Ph III study|url=https://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/enobosarm-fails-endpoints-in-ph-iii-study|work=The Pharma Letter|date=20 August 2013|language=en}}</ref> In October 2013 the company laid off around 60% of its 88 person workforce,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=John|title=Struggling GTx axes 53 staffers in restructuring after PhIII failures|url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/biotech/struggling-gtx-axes-53-staffers-restructuring-after-phiii-failures|work=FierceBiotech|date=2 October 2013|language=en}}</ref> and Steiner resigned 6 months later.<ref name=MBJ2014/> The company had invested around $35 million in the development of the drug.<ref name=MBJ2014>{{cite news|last1=Sheffield|first1=Michael|title=Steiner resigns from GTx|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/memphis/news/2014/04/04/steiner-resigns-from-gtx.html|work=Memphis Business Journal|date=April 4, 2014}}</ref> The company said at that time that is planned to pursue approval of enobosarm in Europe; the company was also still developing GTx-758 for castration-resistant prostate cancer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garde|first1=Damian|title=GTx's CEO finds the door as the company moves on from a PhIII failure |url=https://www.fiercebiotech.com/financials/gtx-s-ceo-finds-door-as-company-moves-on-from-a-phiii-failure|work=FierceBiotech|date=4 April 2014|language=en}}</ref>
In 2016 GTx began Phase II trials, to see if enosobarm might be effective to treat stress uninary incontinence in women.<ref>{{cite news|title=GTx begins Phase II trial of enobosarm to treat women with stress urinary incontinence - Drug Development Technology|url=https://www.drugdevelopment-technology.com/news/newsgtx-begins-phase-ii-trial-of-enobosarm-to-treat-women-with-stress-urinary-incontinence-4785216/|work=Drug Development Technology|date=14 January 2016}}</ref>
