{{Infobox scientist | name = Mabel Purefoy FitzGerald | birth_date = {{Birth date|1872|08|03|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Preston Candover]], [[Hampshire]], England | death_date = {{Death date and age|1973|08|24|1872|08|03|df=y}} | death_place = [[Oxford]], England | nationality = British | fields = [[Physiology]], [[pathology]] }}
'''Mabel Purefoy FitzGerald''' (3 August 1872 – 24 August 1973)<ref name="OxfordDNB">{{cite web|last=Torrance|first=R. W.|title=FitzGerald, Mabel Purefoy (1872–1973)|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/57537|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref> was a British [[physiologist]] and [[clinical pathologist]] best known for her work on the [[Respiration (physiology)|physiology of respiration]]. She became the second female member of the [[American Physiological Society]] in 1913.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Appel|first1=Toby A.|last2=Cassidy|first2=Marie M.|last3=Tidball|first3=M.Elizabeth|title=History of the American Physiological Society|chapter=Women in Physiology|year=1987|publisher=Springer|location=New York|isbn=9781461475767|pages=381–390|chapterurl=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4614-7576-7_14}}</ref>
== Early life and education == Mabel FitzGerald was born in 1872 in [[Preston Candover]] near [[Basingstoke]]. She was educated at home, as was typical for upper and middle class girls in her time. In 1895, both her parents died and Mabel moved to [[Oxford]] with her sisters in 1896.<ref name="OxfordDNB" /> She began to teach herself chemistry and biology from books, as well as attending classes at [[Oxford University]] between 1896 and 1899, even though women were not yet allowed to receive degrees.<ref name="Ogilvie2000"/> She continued her studies at the [[University of Copenhagen]], [[Cambridge University]] and [[New York University]].<ref name="Ogilvie2000">{{cite book|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science: Pioneering Lives from Ancient Times to the Mid-Twentieth Century|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|pages=450–451|isbn=0415920388|editor=Marilyn Ogilvie|editor2=Joy Harvey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmfyK0QtsRAC&lpg=PA450&dq=Mabel%20Purefoy%20FitzGerald%20Physiological%20Society&pg=PA450}}</ref>
== Work == FitzGerald began to work with [[Francis Gotch]] at the physiology department in Oxford. Gotch also helped her get a paper published by the [[Royal Society]] in 1906.<ref name="Ogilvie2000" />
From 1904, FitzGerald worked with [[John Scott Haldane]] on measuring the [[carbon dioxide tension]] in the human lung. After studying the differences between healthy and ill people, the two continued to investigate the effects of altitude on respiration; it is this work that they are most famous for. FitzGerald's observations of the effects of full altitude acclimatization on carbon dioxide tension and [[haemoglobin]] remain accepted today.<ref name="OxfordDNB" />
In 1907, FitzGerald was awarded a Rockefeller travelling scholarship, which allowed her to work in New York and Toronto.<ref name="Ogilvie2000" />
In 1911 she participated, along with [[Claude Gordon Douglas|C. Gordon Douglas]] and several other scientists, in a Colorado expedition led by John Scott Haldane to investigate human respiration at high altitudes.<ref>{{cite journal|author=West, John B.|title=Centenary of the Anglo-American high-altitude expedition to Pikes Peak|date=31 October 2011|journal=Experimental Physiology|doi=10.1113/expphysiol.2011.058776}}</ref>
In the summer of 1913 in North Carolina, she made measurements on the breathing and the blood of a total of 43 adult residents chosen from three different locations in the Southern Appalachian chain.<ref>{{cite journal|author=FitzGerald, M. P.|year=1914|title=Further observations on the changes in the breathing and the blood at various high altitudes|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London. Series B, Containing Papers of a Biological Character|volume=88|issue=602|pages=248–258|jstor=80707}}</ref>
== Later life == FitzGerald returned to the UK in 1915 to serve as a clinical pathologist at the Edinburgh infirmary, a position that was empty because of [[World War I]]. She did not publish any more papers and remained out of contact with the physiology community even after her return to Oxford in 1930.<ref name="Ogilvie2000" />
In 1961, on the centenary of Haldane's birth, her work was rediscovered. In 1972, at 100 years old, she received an honorary MA from Oxford University, 75 years after she had attended classes there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oxford Degree: 75 Years Later|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1346&dat=19721225&id=tXFOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dvoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7038,7804671|newspaper=Lakeland Ledger|date=December 25, 1972}}</ref> She was also made a member of [[The Physiological Society]].<ref name="OxfordDNB" />
== Nachlass == {{blockquote|After her death R. W. Torrance was asked to look at her scientific apparatus and papers in the house at 12 [[Crick Road]]. ... The apparatus formed the tools of her trade as a physiologist studying acclimatizations at high altitude, including an [[altimeter]], [[Wiktionary:haemoglobinometer|haemoglobinometer]], [[haemocytometer]], and the two hemi-Haldane apparatuses she had used in North Carolina. There was a trunk full of family diaries including her own and many letters including some about scientific work from Haldane, Douglas, Gotch, Mann, [[Yandell Henderson|Henderson]] and [[Charles Scott Sherrington|Sherrington]]. This material is now in the [[Bodleian Library]]. There was also correspondence with [[William Osler|Osler]] for whom she collected medical books.<ref>{{cite book|author=O'Connor, W. J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KrToAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA111||year=1991|title=British Physiologists 1885–1914: A Biographical Dictionary|page=111}} Gustav Mann (1864–1921) worked with Gotch from 1894 to 1908 in Oxford and then in 1908 became Professor of Physiology at [[Tulane University]] in [[New Orleans]].</ref>}}
== Selected publications == * {{cite journal|last=FitzGerald|first=MP|last2=Haldane|first2=JS|title=The normal alveolar carbonic acid pressure in man|journal=The Journal of Physiology|year=1905|volume=32|pages=486–494|url=http://jp.physoc.org/content/32/5-6/486.full.pdf|issue=5–6|pmid=16992788|pmc=1465735|doi=10.1113/jphysiol.1905.sp001095}} * {{cite journal|last=FitzGerald|first=MP|title=The changes in the breathing and the blood at various high altitudes|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London|year=1913|volume=203|series=Series B, Containing Papers of a Biological Character|pages=351–371|url=http://rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/203/294-302/351.full.pdf|doi=10.1098/rstb.1913.0008|issue=294–302}} * {{cite journal|last=FitzGerald|first=MP|title=Further observations on the changes in the breathing and the blood at various high altitudes|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|year=1914|volume=88|series=Series B, Containing Papers of a Biological Character|pages=248–258|url=http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/88/602/248.full.pdf|issue=602|bibcode=1914RSPSB..88..248P|doi=10.1098/rspb.1914.0072}}
